t Plant, first constructed in 1988, provides sanitation services to customers of the Lake Arrowhead Community Services District.  The wastewater processes at the Plant include both solids and liquids handling and include:
?    Preliminary treatment;
?    Primary treatment;
?    Secondary treatment;
?    Sludge thickening;
?    Sludge dewatering; and
?    Chlorination.

The final, treated effluent is discharged to percolation ponds along the Mojave River.

Chlorination System Description
Chlorine is stored in three one-ton containers in the Chlorination and Pump Building.  As previously shown, in Figure ES-2, the Chlorination and Pump Building is located to the back of the Plant (on the North side).  The Grass Valley Wastewater Treatment Plant injects gaseous chlorine into water to generate a chlorinated water solution which is then used for a variety of purposes onsite, primarily for final effluent disinfection.  Chlorine gas from a one ton container is pulled through a vacuum regulator assembly (mounted directly on the main container valve) under vacuum to one of three chlorinators.  The vacuum regulator serves to reduce line pressure and regulate it to a constant vacuum.  The vacuum is generated by a venturi mixer that mixes the gaseous chlorine with Plant effluent water (resulting in the chlorine solution).  The resulting chlorine solution is then distributed to one of three points of use:
?    Effluent disinfection in the chlorine contact tank;
?    Odor control at the gravity thickeners and headworks; and
?    Filter fly control and to aid in removing excess filter growth at the trickling filters.

Figure ES-3 presents a Simplified Block Flow Diagram for the Use of Chlorine at the Grass Valley Wastewater Treatment Plant.

